    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-11-11T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-11-11T20:00:00-05:00" n="797"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d797">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/11–1248: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-11-12T09:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 12, 1948—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 12—1:56 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2177. We are already receiving queries from prominent Chinese Government
                    officials who believe their lives would be endangered in the event of Communist
                    occupation of Nanking or of protracted and extreme civil disorders in the city
                    as to the possibility of seeking asylum in the Embassy. We are confident we will
                    receive additional such queries and that the numbers might well run into the
                    hundreds. We propose unless instructed by the Department to the contrary to
                    follow the precedent of Kunming case involving the assassination of Wen I-to
                    during the summer of 1947<note n="48" xml:id="d797fn48">July 1946; see despatch
                        No. 22, August 2, 1946, from the Ambassador in China, <ref
                            target="frus1946v09#pg_1440">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1946, <hi rend="smallcaps"
                                >ix</hi>, p. 1440</ref>.</note> and afford asylum only in cases
                    where there is a clearly demonstrable imminent threat of death.</p>
                <p>Department’s guidance and instructions would be appreciated.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
